In Spring, bean scope defines:

How many instances of a bean are created
How long the bean lives in the container
🔹 @Scope Annotation

Used to define the scope of a bean.

✔ Can be applied at:

Class level (@Component, @Service, etc.)
Method level (@Bean)
✅ Class-Level Example
@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class Emp {
}
✅ Method-Level Example
@Bean("duster")
@Scope("prototype")
public Duster getDuster() {
    return new Duster();
}
🔹 Types of Bean Scopes
1. 🟢 Singleton (Default)
Only ONE instance per Spring container
Shared across the entire application
Default scope (no need to specify)


By default, singleton beans are eagerly initialized at startup
BUT you can make them lazy using:
@Lazy
@Component
public class MyBean {
}
✅ Behavior:
Emp e1 = context.getBean(Emp.class);
Emp e2 = context.getBean(Emp.class);

// e1 == e2 → TRUE (same object)
2. 🔵 Prototype
New instance every time getBean() is called
Not shared
✅ Behavior:
Emp e1 = context.getBean(Emp.class);
Emp e2 = context.getBean(Emp.class);

// e1 == e2 → FALSE (different objects)
⚠️ Important Correction:

✔ Prototype beans are created on demand (lazy by nature)
✔ BUT Spring does NOT manage full lifecycle:

👉 @PreDestroy is NOT called automatically for prototype beans

🔹 Key Differences 
| Feature        | Singleton                         | Prototype         |
| -------------- | --------------------------------- | ----------------- |
| Instances      | One per container                 | New every request |
| Default?       | Yes                               |  No               |
| Initialization | Eager (default) / Lazy (optional) | Lazy              |
| Shared         | Yes                               | No                |
| @PreDestroy    | Called                            |  Not called       |
